=== notes on the two bugs this run exists to fix ===
BUG 1 (dedup). export_hyperbolic_atlas.py keyed on the canonical vertex configuration and kept one map
per config. In H2 the vertex figure does not determine the tiling, so distinct tilings sharing a figure
were discarded. 4.4.4.6 is the case AL spotted: the engine found a 1-uniform tiling AND a 2-uniform one
whose every vertex is 4.4.4.6; only the first shipped.

BUG 2 (k labels). The block's own k was trusted. Reading the vertex orbits off the developed patch shows
four of the 17 shipped "k=2" entries have three distinct vertex-ball types, hence k>=3. Also
ctrnact-01_46-4ab-1 is emitted as a k=1 BLOCK yet develops to a 2-orbit tiling. The hyperbolic branch's
own k accounting is not reliable; k is now read off the patch.

Why "#distinct r-ball codes <= #vertex orbits" is sound: two vertices in one symmetry orbit have
isomorphic balls of every radius, so distinct balls force distinct orbits. The count is a LOWER bound
needing no trust in the solver.

Validation of the identity invariant (hyperbolic_identity.py):
  (a) all 42 shipped k=1 entries yield exactly ONE ball code at every radius their patch supports —
      root-independence, and a check on the developer at the same time;
  (b) one record developed to boundR 0.99 / 0.995 / 0.998 gives code sets in subset relation at every
      shared radius, never a contradiction;
  (c) it separates the 4.4.4.6 pair, agreeing with an independent face-corona count (interior squares
      have 0 or 2 hexagon neighbours in one, 1 or 2 in the other).

BUG 3, found while fixing 1 and 2 (gate). The tileability gate ran on the shipped boundR=0.95 patch and
demanded 40 faces. That disk holds FOUR faces of {8,4} and five of {5,5}, so the gate was throwing out
the regular tilings and keeping finely-divided folds. Re-grown to 0.99+ every real tiling fills the disk
(arc 0 deg). Gate now runs on the deep development.
